{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"314f7cda-9f45-4022-8ddd-36454f46a2c9","content":"\n\nThe new command passes platform-specific options after `--`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| VSTest flag | Testing Platform equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**Required NuGet packages** in your test project:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```\n\nAnd enable the `dotnet test` bridge:\n\n```xml\n<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n```\n\n`--filter` stays *before* `--` since `dotnet test` handles it natively.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"567ffc17-9ccd-4b65-993c-cba9ce6f22d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing platform migration, not a code change task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences:\n- `--filter` → `--filter`(same)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n\n\n- `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nFor .NET 8, you'll typically run tests through `dotnet test` if you enable the testing platform support in your project file, though the native approach is using `dotnet run` or calling the test executable directly.\n\nWhen using `dotnet test` with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you pass arguments after `--` to reach the test platform itself. If you're running the test project directly instead, the arguments go straight to the executable without that separator. Now I'm mapping out the equivalent command-line arguments between VSTest and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, showing how features like trx reporting, code coverage, and crash/hang dumps translate to the new platform's syntax. I also need to note the required NuGet packages for each feature to work properly.","outputTokens":1314},"id":"6ad84a1e-2786-449c-8e45-206ab7a8fb17","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:51:25.881Z","parentId":"84942ad5-bb18-4769-b527-8b166cbd1a97"}
